\ul\b 3. Getting Started:\par
\line\fs24 3.1) Requirements:\ulnone\b0  \ul\b\fs40\par
\ulnone\b0\fs24\tab ECS Swarms makes use of ECS and DOTS, what this means is that in order to make use of ECS Swarms you must install some packages nessesary for ECS and DOTS. The two packages that are required are\b  Hybrid Renderer \b0 and \b Havok Physics for Unity \b0 (Unity Physics also works, but Havok Physics for Unity is a bit faster, while also having some additional licensing requirements). This means that you must also be using Unity version 2020.1.9f1 or later, as that is the last version that both of those packages are available for.\par
\tab However, both of these packages are currently in the preview stages and have not had their full release yet. This means that you need to turn on \b Enable Preview Packages \b0 in the package manager. To do this, open your Unity project and navigate to \b Window \b0 > \b Package Manager \b0 > \b Settings (gear icon) \b0 > \b Advanced Project Settings\b0 . Then you can enable the \b Enable Preview Packages \b0 settings.\par
\tab To install the Hybrid Renderer package, open your Unity project and navigate to \b Window \b0 > \b Package Manager \b0 > \b +\b0  > \b Add Package From git URL\b0 . Then enter \f2 com.unity.rendering.hybrid@0.50.0-preview.44 \f1 (the version may change, however after installing this there will be an option to update to the latest version. If you would like the documentation for the \b Hybrid Renderer\b0 , you can find it at {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.rendering.hybrid@latest/ }}{\fldrslt{https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.rendering.hybrid@latest/\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs24 .\par
\tab To install the Physics package, open your Unity project and navigate to \b Window \b0 > \b Package Manager\b0 , then set \b Packages \b0 to \b Unity Registry\b0 . Then search for "Physics" and install the \b Havok Physics for Unity \b0 package (note that you must have enabled the Enable Pre-release Packages setting in order to have this appear in the search). If you would like the documentation for this Physics package, you can find it at {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.physics@latest/ }}{\fldrslt{https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.physics@latest/\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs24 .\par
\tab You will also want to sure your project is made to render with either URP (Universal Render Pipeline) or HDRP (High Definition Render Pipeline), this is because Hybrid Renderer only supports those options, meaning that assets made for the Built-in render pipeline may not be compatible.\ul\b\par
\ulnone\b0\par
\ul\b 3.2) Using ECS Swarms:\ulnone\b0  \par
\tab Using ECS Swarms once you have DOTS set-up is quite simple. All you need to do is place a \b Swarm Settings\b0  component on the GameObject you wish to use as a prefab for your swarms. After adding the swarms settings component, you can tweak the values and settings to whatever you would like. You must also click the \b ConvertToEntity \b0 toggle button, in order to mark this GameObject to be converted to an ECS entity. Then save that GameObject as a prefab.\par
\tab After creating your swarm prefab, you must now create a swarm spawner. To do this add a \b Swarm Spawner\b0  component to any GameObject in your scene. You will want to fill in the data for the prefab to spawn, the area to spawn in, and the count to spawn. Make sure to also toggle \b ConvertToEntity \b0 on this GameObject.\par
\tab That's really all you need to get started, it's that simple! In addition, you can also add the \b Swarm Node \b0 components to GameObjects, this will cause various effects on nearby swarms based on the node's tag attribute. However, those GameObjects must also have \b ConvertToEntity \b0 enabled.\par
